article.description: Jason Kidd hit consecutive 3-pointers to ignite a late run that carried the New Jersey Nets to a franchise-record 10th straight home win, 116-102 over the Atlanta Hawks on Sunday night.

article.headline: Another flagrant foul puts Martin back on bench
article.linkText: Nets dump Hawks; Martin gets two-game suspension
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- A franchise-record 10-game home winning streak and closing in on a playoff berth meant little to the New Jersey Nets in the wake of another flagrant foul on Kenyon Martin.
Martin

Martin picked up his sixth flagrant foul of the season in the Nets' 116-102 win over the Atlanta Hawks on Sunday, and it put a damper on any thought of celebrating either the winning streak or being on the verge of their first postseason berth since 1997-98. Martin got this flagrant for throwing an elbow at the face of Shareef Abdur-Rahim with 9:06 left in the game. Martin was going up for a shot and he appeared to be fouled by Abdur-Rahim. If the call is upheld, Martin will have eight flagrant-foul points, mandating a two-game suspension. "We felt that he lifted his elbow as if to throw it at the defensive player," crew chief Dick Bavetta said. "From my position, I did not see contact made. However, after a discussion with my two partners, we decided contact was in fact made." Martin, who met with NBA officials last week to ask for a fair shake, refused to discuss the incident. "I'm not talking about it," said Martin, who has already been suspended for five games because of flagrant fouls. Abdur-Rahim said that Martin definitely swung through with his elbow. "I guess whether you make contact or not that's a flagrant," said Abdur-Rahim, who led the Hawks with 30 points. "That's their rule." Nets coach Byron Scott said he knew Martin would get a flagrant. "I have to sit down with Kenyon and talk to him and find out what he is thinking," Scott said. "I have to get him to understand that he can't react negatively to things that are going on on the court." If Scott can't convince him to change his ways, maybe Martin will realize the need when he sees his pay stubs. If Martin is banished for two more games, he will have lost $347,057.55 in combined salary losses and fines from flagrant fouls. Nets center Aaron Williams said officials also need to cut Martin some slack. He said a technical foul should have been called on Martin instead of a flagrant. "It's getting ridiculous," Williams said. "I have never seen so many flagrant fouls called on a guy. It's ridiculous, especially tonight." Abdur-Rahim hit both free throws after the flagrant and then scored in the lane to give the Hawks a 91-90 lead. Kidd, 1-for-10 from the field in the first half, then took over, hitting consecutive 3-pointers to ignite a 24-7 spurt that put the game away. Martin made his final minutes useful. He scored six of eight points after Kidd's 3s to allow the Nets to pull away. "Everybody understands he is a marked man," Kidd said of Martin. "He has to understand that, too." The call made almost everyone forget about the playoffs. New Jersey will clinch a playoff berth with either its next win or a Miami loss. The only thing that prevented New Jersey from clinching on Sunday was a quirky tiebreaker in case it finished in a three-way tie for the eighth playoff spot with the Heat and another team. Kidd had 19 of his 22 points in the second half, and he added 15 assists. Kerry Kittles also had 22 points, and Martin 16 as the Nets had seven players score in double figures. Jason Terry added 17 points for Hawks, who had a three-game winning streak snapped in losing for only the second time in eight games. Game notes
Abdur-Rahim rejoined the team after missing the Hawks' home victory Saturday over Chicago because he was in California for the birth of his son. ... Nets center Todd MacCulloch played for the first time since going on the injured list on Feb. 21 with plantar fascitis. The Nets were 8-8 without him. ... Williams, who has been starting for MacCulloch, scored 10 of New Jersey's first 12 points while hitting all six of his first-half shots. He finished with 14. MacCulloch had 10. ... New Jersey's old record for consecutive home wins was set in 1999-2000. ... The Nets are 29-6 at home this season. ... Atlanta is 8-4 this month. ... The Hawks are 9-27 on the road.
